SIMPLE: mat
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mat
<hw>Mat</hw> <pr>(m⟦acr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Matte</er>.]</ety> <def>A name given by coppersmiths to an alloy of
copper, tin, iron, etc., usually called <xex>white metal</xex>.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>matt</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mat
<hw>Mat</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF. See 4th <er>Mate</er>.]</ety>
<def>Cast down; dejected; overthrown; slain.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he saw them so piteous and so <qex>maat</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mat
<hw>Mat</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>matt</ets>, <ets>meatt</ets>,
fr. L. <ets>matta</ets> a mat made of rushes.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
thick flat fabric of sedge, rushes, flags, husks, straw, hemp, or
similar material, placed on the floor and used for wiping and cleaning
shoes at the door, for covering the floor of a hall or room to protect
its surface, and for other purposes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any similar flat object made of fabric or other
material, such as rubber or plastic, placed flat on a surface for
various uses, as for covering plant houses, putting beneath dishes or
lamps on a table, securing rigging from friction, and the
like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything growing thickly, or closely interwoven, so
as to resemble a mat in form or texture; <as>as, a <ex>mat</ex> of
weeds; a <ex>mat</ex> of hair.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An ornamental border made of paper, pasteboard,
metal, etc., put under the glass which covers a framed picture; <as>as,
the <ex>mat</ex> of a daguerreotype</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mat grass</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A
low, tufted, European grass (<spn>Nardus stricta</spn>)</cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Same as <er>Matweed</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mat
rush</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of rush (<spn>Scirpus
lacustris</spn>) used in England for making mats.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mat
<hw>Mat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Matted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Matting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover or lay with
mats.</def> <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To twist, twine, or felt together; to interweave
into, or like, a mat; to entangle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And o'er his eyebrows hung his <qex>matted</qex> hair.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mat
<hw>Mat</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow thick together; to become
interwoven or felted together like a mat, as hair when wetted with a
sticky substance; <as>as, a long-haired cat whose fur is
<ex>matted</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matabeles</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Matabele</ent>⟦br⟧
